{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2331"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2331"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.02,0.27,0.16,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56179"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2331"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41732"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"2136"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17812"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56179"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of worsening generalised deep pain in the anterior part of her right groin, involving the ipsilateral anteromedial upper thigh and buttock. The pain is exacerbated by standing from a sitting position and movement of her right leg. The pain has now started to interfere with her sleep. She also notes increased stiffness in the right leg in the morning, which worsens with movement. Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes, hyperlipidaemia, and obesity. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she has pain and reduced range of motion of hip flexion, extension, and internal rotation on the right side. The straight-leg-raise test causes pain in the right leg but not paraesthesia. There are no areas of muscle tenderness or tightness. Power, reflexes, and sensation are normal bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lumbar disc herniation","Rheumatoid arthritis","Piriformis syndrome","Ischial bursitis","Right hip osteoarthritis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a textbook case of hip \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E (OA), with pain, aching, stiffness, and restricted movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETypically, pain associated with hip OA is felt deep in the anterior groin but may also involve the upper thigh (medial or lateral) and less commonly the buttock. This is further supported by limitation of hip flexion, extension and internal rotation. Pain which affects sleep and morning joint stiffness which worsens with movement should also alert the clinician to the possibility of arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschial bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an uncommon pathology involving inflammation of the Ischio-gluteal bursa. This condition occurs most frequently in individuals with a sedentary lifestyle. The pain of ischial bursitis is reproduced by palpation of the ischial region, sitting and stretching of the hamstring muscle (The ischial tuberosity is the origin of the hamstring); ie bending, climbing stairs and running. The hallmarks of bursitis are tenderness, lateral hip pain and a positive Ober\u0027s test (tenderness over the tensor fascia latae).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPiriformis syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Eis another uncommon condition characterized by \u201csciatic symptoms\u201d due to compression of the sciatic nerve at the hip. The pain of piriformis syndrome is reproduced by the FAIR manoeuvre; that is reproduction of pain on Flexion, Adduction and Internal Rotation of the hip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Elumbar disc herniation\u003C/strong\u003E radicular pain down the affected limb would be expected. There would be neurological deficits and the straight leg raise to produce pain and paraesthesia ipsilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with symmetrical joint involvement, often affecting the small joints of the hands and feet initially. It is associated with prolonged morning stiffness that improves with movement, unlike the stiffness in osteoarthritis, which worsens with activity. The lack of symmetrical joint involvement and the specific pattern of pain and stiffness in this case make rheumatoid arthritis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Joint pain secondary to osteoarthritis worsens with movement."],"references":["Doherty M. Clinical manifestations and diagnosis of osteoarthritis.\u00a0 In: Hunter D, Ramirez M. Editors.; UptoDate. [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate Inc; 2020 [Cited 18 Jan 2020]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-of-osteoarthritis","Watts E, Patel S, Incavo S. Hip osteoarthritis [Internet]. Orthobullets; 2020 [updated 2020, cited 2021 Jan 15]. Available from:\u00a0https://www.orthobullets.com/recon/5005/hip-osteoarthritis","Ekiz T, Bicici V, Hatioglu C, Yalcin S, Cingoz K. Ischial pain and sitting disability due to ischiogluteal bursitis: visual vignette. Pain physician. 2015;18(4): E657-E8.","Moore D. Lumbar disc herniation [Internet]. Orthobullets; 2020 [updated 2020, cited 2021 Jan 15]. Available from:\u00a0https://www.orthobullets.com/spine/2035/lumbar-disc-herniation.","Abbasi D, Moore D. Osteoporotic vertebral compression fracture [Internet]. Orthobullets; 2020 [updated 2020, cited 2021 Jan 15]. Available from:\u00a0https://www.orthobullets.com/spine/2021/osteoporotic-vertebral-compression-fracture"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41732"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2331"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41732"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T18:29:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T16:19:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2331"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56179"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":nu